               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1012" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1012" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1012" type="surname" value="MANSFIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1012" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MANSFIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an ironmonger, and live in Providence-cot-tage, Vauxhall Bridge-road—the prisoner worked for me. On the 22nd of August, 1837, I gave him 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. In silver, and 10<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. In copper, to get some iron—he took a truck with him—in about an hour I was going down the next street, and found the truck—I never received the iron, nor saw any more of him till last summer, when I met him, and spoke to him—he asked my forgiveness—I turned round to look for a policeman, and he got off—he has since been taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did not you agree to take it of me as I could pay you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I came to no agreement—I never received any money—you offered me 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. last Thursday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1013" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1013" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1013" type="surname" value="DRAKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1013" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS DRAKE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I went after the prisoner, and took him—he said if the prosecutor would forgive him he would pay him—the prosecutor said he should go on with it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I received very little wages from him—I forgot what he owed me, and could not summons him for it, and left him—he afterwards came and got me to work for him again, and gave me 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. of what he owed me—I left him again in about a month—he met me one Saturday morning, and asked if I was out of work—I said yes—he said if I came down on Monday morning he would give me a job, which I did and worked till Wednesday morning—he gave me 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. to get iron for him, and I kept it for my back wages.</p>
